The HTMLHeaderTextSplitter is a "structure-aware" splitter. Unlike other splitters that look for characters like newlines or spaces, this one looks for HTML tags (like <h1>, <h2>, <h3>) to decide where to cut the text.
It is incredibly helpful because it keeps the "heading" information attached to the text as metadata. This means your AI doesn't just see a random paragraph; it knows exactly which section of the webpage that paragraph belongs to.
1. How It Works
You define a "mapping" of which HTML tags you want to split on and what you want to call those headers in your metadata.
from langchain_text_splitters import HTMLHeaderTextSplitter

# 1. Define the "Rules": Split on <h1> and <h2>
headers_to_split_on = [
    ("h1", "Header 1"),
    ("h2", "Header 2"),
]

# 2. Initialize the splitter
html_splitter = HTMLHeaderTextSplitter(headers_to_split_on=headers_to_split_on)

# 3. Input HTML
html_string = """
<html>
    <body>
        <h1>Main Topic: AI</h1>
        <p>AI is changing the world.</p>
        <h2>Subtopic: Pydantic</h2>
        <p>Pydantic helps with data validation.</p>
    </body>
</html>
"""

# 4. Split the text
splits = html_splitter.split_text(html_string)

for chunk in splits:
    print(f"Content: {chunk.page_content}")
    print(f"Metadata: {chunk.metadata}\n")

Output Example:
 * Chunk 1 Metadata: {'Header 1': 'Main Topic: AI'}
 * Chunk 2 Metadata: {'Header 1': 'Main Topic: AI', 'Header 2': 'Subtopic: Pydantic'}
2. Using Pydantic for "Strict" HTML Ingestion
Since web headers can be messy (containing weird symbols or being too long), you can use Pydantic to clean the metadata generated by the HTMLHeaderTextSplitter.
from pydantic import BaseModel, Field

class CleanWebMetadata(BaseModel):
    header_1: str = Field(alias="Header 1", default="General")
    header_2: str = Field(alias="Header 2", default="General")

# After splitting, you validate the metadata
for doc in splits:
    try:
        # Pydantic validates and organizes the header info
        clean_meta = CleanWebMetadata(**doc.metadata)
        doc.metadata = clean_meta.model_dump()
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Metadata was too messy to save: {e}")

3. Why use this over a normal Text Splitter?
| Feature | RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter | HTMLHeaderTextSplitter |
|---|---|---|
| Awareness | Blind to HTML structure. | Knows the difference between a title and a paragraph. |
| Metadata | Keeps the same metadata for all chunks. | Changes metadata based on the current section. |
| Context | Context is lost if headers are cut. | Preserves context by attaching header names to every chunk. |
| Best For | Plain text / General documents. | Articles, Documentation, and Blogs. |
The "Two-Step" Pro Move
Often, a single section (like under an <h2>) is still too long for an LLM. Most developers do this:
 * Use HTMLHeaderTextSplitter to get the Semantic Sections.
 * Use RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter to break those sections into smaller Token Chunks.
This ensures every small chunk knows exactly which <h1> and <h2> it came from.
> Wit's End: Using a normal splitter on HTML is like shredding a newspaper and trying to guess which article a fragment belongs to. HTMLHeaderTextSplitter is like cutting the newspaper into neat, labeled clippings.

